results.notes:
Growing on a well-rotted, mossy Tsuga canadensis stump near rotten Phaeolus schweinitzii. 1 mature basidiocarp with associated primordia. Cap dry with a chalky texture; 32.6 mm wide and 13.3 mm tall. Pores yellow, bruising quickly blue before turning reddish-brown; short-decurrent; up to 3.0 mm deep. Tubes and mouths concolorous. Stem dry; 29.1 mm long and 10.6 mm wide at the widest. Basal mycelium yellow. Context white initially and bruising blue in all parts before fading to a dull yellow-brown. Taste not distinctive. Odor faintly fruity. Not fluorescing under UV.

results.notes:
Found in clay soil among hardwood trees, primarily white oaks and hickories. Scattered, a few small groups of two or three.

Cap and stem are firm.

Cap surface is smooth and dry.

Cap flesh is white. Stem flesh is white with very faint yellow tint.

Skin on cap is very thin. Tubes are very short. Pores are yellow/orange in younger specimens, reddish in older. Tubes are small diameter, surface appears uniform color and smooth.

Cap surface, cap flesh, stem surface, stem flesh do not stain, even after one hour. Pores quickly stain dark blue, fading to black.

Taste is mild. No particular odor.

There was a noticeable lack of insect activity in all specimens.

Stems are finely reticulated. Color is darker toward base, with a pale area just below the cap. White region at base. Mycelium white.

Observed by Linda Souhrada and Don Abrams.
